Text.Value: I am ready to be judged.
O Hail, true Chosen. May you bring death wherever you walk.
Orin sent me here to be baptised by Bhaal. Does her word count for nothing?
You disappoint me, child of Bhaal. I had heard such tales of you - tales of grandeur, and vile glory.
Can it be - Belynne herself, reduced to a spectre...
I do not murder innocents. I save them.
You disappoint me, child of Murder. I expected more of your return.
Sarevok Anchev. How are you still alive?
*Is he your cousin? Great-uncle? Brother, even? Bhaal's bilious waters are always a little murky.*
IMPUDENCE!
I couldn't bring myself to harvest body parts. Not even for a god.
You wished to deceive Sarevok and your allies? The intent pleases, but the execution lacks finesse.
We'll find a third way. Would you two like to kill the old man, or shall I?
I have heard it said you lost your memories. Let me revive them.
Only because I can no longer bear to look you in the eye.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Jaheira bows before Sarevok, annoyed with the player.
EditorData.NodeContext: Despite yourself, the player has intimidated you into bowing before an old enemy. Irritated, won't be cowed long

Text.Value: But the line is not ended... You carry him with you, deep within. In your Divine Essence.
This was Orin's tribunal. She was judged, and she was found exceptional.
I'd like to meet Orin. Where can I find her?
You wish to become an Unholy Assassin of Bhaal. So, approach and be judged.
Exquisite. I claim afore Father that I desire all deaths equally. In my private worship, though, I have found myself turning again and again to prayers for her demise.
We're not here to dig up old feuds. I seek a path to the Temple of Bhaal.
The deed is done - the details don't matter.
Harper worm... the abdicating hero... your keen sense for this city has withered in your absence.
You have earned the right to stand before Bhaal's tribunal.
Your face bears the marks of many years, Jaheira. Your wit, however, does not.
She is the child of my child, and your blood kin.
First, I ended its sorry existence. Then, I cut the hand from its corpse.
With a smile on my face, and pleasure in my heart.
Orin sent me here to be baptised by Bhaal. What must I do?
She will not bend to your will. No matter - it will be my pleasure to break you both, instead. In my Father's name.
But the truth of Bhaal's will remains. Any Bhaalspawn who can kill a Chosen has a hope of becoming the Chosen themselves.
Slow thy tongue, dread sister of mine. This pretender would foist itself upon us willingly, ill-met, but no stranger to slaughter.
I answer for myself, Sarevok - and Minsc and Jaheira answer to me. They won't be a problem.
A servant to the cause. A master of the craft.
That's horrible. No child should have to go through that.
I see why Orin spoke of you with daggered spite.
In times past I was Bhaal's Deathbringer - his acolyte. And you, his favourite child.
The Tribunal bears witness, aspirant - do not disappoint us.
Are you the reason there are so many murders in the city?
Our cult survived, festering beneath the city, with me as the Gate's everlasting poison.
The cult survived, festering beneath the city, with me as the Gate's everlasting poison.
Is it to be death, then? A better alternative to watching this sick family reunion.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Jaheira bows before Sarevok, annoyed with the player.

Text.Value: What trials are set upon them?
Don't tell me I am to be tested again.
Harper worm... the abdicating hero... your keen sense for this city has withered in your absence.
He will not bend to your will. No matter - it will be my pleasure to break you both, instead. In my Father's name.
I didn't come here to become embroiled in your family drama - I came here to be baptised by Bhaal.
I never thought I'd see this. The Grand Harper, brought to her knees before me.
I've come to slay her. Where is she?
And yet you share a Father - her relation to you is as strong as it is to me, blood kin. Perhaps stronger.
What exactly is an Unholy Assassin?
I answer for myself, Sarevok - and Jaheira answers to me. She won't be a problem.
And so the idiot ranger raises his weapon against Sarevok once more.
We have a sacrifice prepared for you, child of Murder. Let us celebrate your becoming.
Sarevok once fancied himself Bhaal's Chosen, until we put him in his place. Feel no shame for forgetting him - history shall do the same.

EditorData.NodeContext: Jeering, has absolutely no time for Sarevok

Text.Value: She hungered for Bhaal's favour more than anyone I'd ever known. But her daughter, Orin, hungered even more.
I thank you for killing my granddaughter. She could not have been dispatched by better. Nor could I.
I can see why Bhaal chose Orin.
Silence, spawn. Our undeaths are not to be admired. They are a punishment for our failures.
What does this judgement involve exactly?
You have been judged.
Spirit of the slaughtered - return to us.
You are unworthy of Bhaal's presence, let alone his trial.
You worshipped Him the way that he would wish - your blood-lust innate, your thirst for butchery unslakable.
But you - your blood is purer than mine ever was. He made you himself. The perfect killer.
Only this time you will fall. And Bhaal will have his offering - by my hand.
That's pure delusion. Bhaal would never anoint you as the Chosen, worm.
Would you like to kill the old man, Minsc, or shall I?
I came here to become an Unholy Assassin, not to clean up after your offspring, Sarevok.
Bhaal's reasons are not for us to question.
Even if I cannot defeat you, perhaps at last he will let me die.
Prodigal servants, each returned to do his bidding eternally.
Not even for a Bhaalspawn.
*Sarevok Anchev. A Bhaalspawn who failed to become Chosen, long ago. A spilled stain of Father's Divine Essence left out to dry.*
My Lord has a new favourite now. My granddaughter, Orin.

EditorData.NodeContext: with resentment - he thinks the Chosen should be him

Text.Value: A long while ago, my wretched sibling brought me back. The fairest of Bhaalspawn, soul-bound me to this husk.
We'll find a third way. Would you two like to kill the old man, Minsc, or shall I?
But for one purpose you are fit indeed - you will make a fine offering to the Murder Lord.
Tell me of my past, I wish to know it.
If you think she needs to be taught a lesson, why don't you teach her yourself?
His most ill-trusted zealots.
Did you know that your daughter was planning to kill Orin?
But no more. For poison is too slow a death. Now is the time for slaughter.
While you wriggled 'neath the city's soil like the worm that you are. It will please my hamster to kill you twice, Sarevok.
You don't have a hope in the Hells of defeating me.
It is a lesson Orin will only learn in death. I wonder if you will be the one to teach her?
This is the court of the Dread Lord's tribunal. I am its custodian.
Know that while I sit here in this husk, and in every moment, experience the crystalline pain of the moment of my death.
His will be done.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [KAYLEIGH] Several member of the tribunal lend their powers to Saverok by reaching out  with their left hand, keeping the other to the temple.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The non-sarevok members of the tribunal lend their powers to sarevok - perhaps one hand to the temple, one outstretched towards sarevok?

Text.Value: And you... Man of Stone. As you stood a statue, a helpless ornament, your city warped. Changed. Became ripe for the plucking.
His ire may be quiet now, and you may not have become his brutal prophet.
That is not for you to question.
What offering was I supposed to bring?
She worships at the heart of Bhaal's domain - the temple of our Lord.
I will make Bhaal proud.
Let us die, Chosen. As only Bhaalspawn can die.
I want to become an Unholy Assassin. What must I do?
These two have long meddled in my affairs - and my father's.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'These two' refers to Minsc and Jaheira

Text.Value: My idol, my hero, even in death.
Wait, how do you know each other?
Come, child of Murder, let me lead you in Bhaal's worship.
I know this one well. I have travelled in her company. Whatever else may be said of her, she answers to no one but herself.
We have a sacrifice prepared for you, child of Murder. Let us celebrate your becoming.
But the company you keep has tainted you, and pulled you from our Father's grace.
But I do bring an offering, Sarevok. You've already met Jaheira.
You will die as you have lived, a heretic, forgotten, and unloved. Blood to blood is Bhaal's sacrifice. And I shall be the knife that spills it.
And as she toyed with her dead mother's hand, a deep quiver rose up through her throat - the Lord of Murder speaking through the child.
The details are everything. Anyone can kill - not everyone can make murder an act of worship.
You are mistaken. An offering must be made.
I'm looking for Orin. Is she here?
This is a sacrifice my father has long lusted for. But it is not the giving of their lives that will please Bhaal - it is the taking.
Orin's gift surpassed even her mother's. Her mother knew this, and she could not bear it.
How does it feel to be surpassed by your own grandchild?
She has already challenged me herself. We will duel to the death.
A test. To prove your worth to Bhaal.
Our lord does not care for beauty. Bhaal cares only for death. Death in numbers. Death in droves.
Slowly and painfully. I savoured every scream.
You are as stupid as I recall, man of stone.
Your offering pleases Lord Bhaal. Your words delight him.

I see you have not embraced your birthright yet. Perhaps with my stewardship,
Father will bless you yet.
You're out of luck. Bhaal's hold over me is gone.
And so the Grand Harper raises her weapons against Sarevok once more.
Fine, Sarevok. If he won't obey - take him as my offering instead.
A pleasing thing, to see these stones stained with the blood of she who disgraced my Father.
I'm looking for Orin. Where can I find her?
You shrink from that which you should revel in. Your devotion to your Father is wanting.
You were blinded by her artistry, her devotion - you believed she worshipped you as much as all the others.
No fooling you, Sarevok. We were actually just deciding which of us should get to kill you.
But my fate is a paradise, compared to the one Father has in store for you.
But you are no mere aspirant. I did not expect to see you again. So it is true. You have returned.
First, I ended its sorry existence. Then, I cut the hand from its corpse.
You are something truly glorious, child.
Fate is written, and I have read it... you shall know soon enough.
I'll prove it to you, Sarevok. ON YOUR KNEES, FILTH.
Not even for a Slayer-Lord.
I brought Jaheira here as an offering for Bhaal.
*Devella was right. Not just an imitator, but Sarevok himself.*
You were never more to my Father than a stinging insect - irritating, but irrelevant. And yet you still scrabble for his attention.
I shall gladly step aside for Orin. I have no interest in pursuing Bhaal's favour.
Attack.
Your words stumble. They hesitate. You lie.
I didn't kill this person. But I will kill you.
If Minsc is certain of one thing, it is that he very much plans on being a problem for Sarevok.
She wronged me. In killing her, you honour our Father with a eulogy of blood.
You were once Bhaal's favourite. You worshipped Him the way that he would wish - your blood-lust innate, your thirst for butchery unslakable.
Come, dread sisters. Let us make a sacrifice of this pretender, for Bhaal will have his offering.
Do you hear that, child? The bloodless vacuum where your Father's love for you should be. You have disappointed him.
I know my like, child of Bhaal - but I needed to see you slaughter, first. To take life and revel in it.
I believe you will be the one to slay Orin.
But you do not belong here. You have brought no offering. You are not fit to be judged.
Attack.
Would you two like to kill the old man, or shall I?
Show us the achievements this child has accomplished in thy unholy name.
I would have thought you understood that, Bhaalspawn. I am disappointed.
My aching bones still feel every spark of pain from the crystalline moment of my death.
Show us the truth of this murderer's intent, and let us judge him for his bloody service.
Show us the truth of this murderer's intent, and let us judge her for her bloody service.
Show us the truth of this murderer's intent, and let us judge them for their bloody service.
But now, you have returned. Tell me, are you here to have your vengeance on my granddaughter?
You were the greatest hope we had for centuries...
The youngest Unholy Assassin ever to follow in Bhaal's bloody trail. And his Chosen.
Sarevok, Bhaal's least favourite son. Still tied to daddy's apron strings, I see.
Debasing Bhaal's enemies wasn't enough? Fine. Let Minsc and Jaheira be my offerings.
What purpose do you have in bringing this heretic to the court of Bhaal? Speak, or death will be your final word.
We'll find a third way. Would you like to kill the old man, Jaheira, or shall I?
She seeks to sacrifice you in our Father's temple.
The holy fool, who purged Bhaal's blessing and ruined their once-perfect form. Your death is a welcome offering here.
She dreams that your corpse will be her masterpiece, but she forgets - before your incident, you were the true master.
We preside over the Tribunal, which has initiated many assassins into the ranks in the Temple. Here we remain until another of our line ends time itself.
An Unholy Assassin of Bhaal has victims, not adversaries.
No, Sarevok - I am here to slay you.
*This man is known to all Baldurians, and his presence sparks dread in the pit of your stomach.*
*Though this city is not your home, this man's infamy is known to you, and his presence sparks dread in the pit of your stomach.*
I know Orin. I killed her.
If I don't recall my past, what need have I of vengeance?
*Sarevok Anchev. A relic of your cursed line, a Bhaalspawn who failed to become Chosen.*
Then what purpose do you serve, Sarevok?
A pleasing thing, to see these stones stained with the blood of he who disgraced my Father.
Then I'll leave.
I heard the screams, I ran to help, afeared for the child's life. But the cries were not Orin's.
And I will be that world-ender.
Do not parley with this madman.
You took this spirit's life, and thus, its voice. So, speak for it. How was this pitiable creature slain?
You get to my age, you have already done everything. Be my guest.
I never thought I'd see this. The Harper and the idiot ranger brought to their knees before me.
There is no better mirror in which to see the true nature of a killer than his victim.
There is no better mirror in which to see the true nature of a killer than her victim.
There is no better mirror in which to see the true nature of a killer than their victim.
Reverence.
Sarevok reclaimed his soul, once - and he still traded it back to his father for a pat on the head. He has earned his second death even more than his first.
We fought already. She bested me, humiliated me, enclosed me in this chamber with Bhaal's unending disappointment. I am a failure to Him.
This one has long meddled in my affairs - and my father's.
Then your devotion to the Murder Lord is unparalleled. And I am in your debt. For you have done me a great service. You have cleared the way for my return.
I sense truth to your words - arrogance, too. Bhaal's children must also learn from him. I had to.
I already killed Orin, what more must I do?
In times past I was Bhaal's Deathbringer - his acolyte. But no more.
Begone. The time has passed.
I have heard of the duel Orin proposed to you. She seeks to sacrifice you in our Father's temple.
What purpose do you have in bringing these heretics to the court of Bhaal? Speak, or death will be your final word.
My very blood, and by extension, His.
We honoured Bhaal with our deaths, but he dragged us into these husked forms, to bring the lash upon the Gate, and nurse his dread cult in its dormant years.
What a treat. Just like your granddaughter was, gargling on her own blood.
And so the Harper and the idiot ranger raise their weapons against Sarevok once more.
You will make a fine offering to the Lord of Murder - his own blood, returned to him, freed of its ungrateful flesh.

Text.Value: Wait, how do you know each other?
You should have killed Orin for what she did.
I understand. I once fell to hubris, as you are falling now. But no more.
Forgive me, child of Bhaal. I forget myself.
It may not be this decade, may not be this century, but a true Spawn, our Dread Father incarnate, will one day be born, and will destroy this city.
Debasing Bhaal's enemies wasn't enough? Fine. Let Minsc be my offering.
We have already smashed Sarevok's soul from his body once. Boo says it is your turn.
I will not worship Bhaal. Though I am his spawn, he is no father of mine.
What fate does Bhaal have in store for me?
Pathetic. You worship death, yet have come back to life.
I never thought I'd see this. The Rashemen wanderer brought to his knees before me.
They will not bend to your will. No matter - it will be my pleasure to break you, instead. In my Father's name.
But I do bring an offering, Sarevok. You've already met Minsc.
LONG MAY HE REIGN.
As you stood a statue, Stone Lord, a helpless ornament, your city changed. Warped. Became ripe for the plucking.
You bear his blood well, child. Your offering pleases Father.
Debasing Bhaal's enemies wasn't enough? Fine. Let Jaheira be my offering.
UNWORTHY.

Text.Value: The weakest worm of a Bhaalspawn, the holy fool. Whelp, know that Bhaal has a worse fate in stall for you than you could ever fear.
And you... Man of Stone. As you stood a statue, a helpless ornament, your city warped. Changed. Became ripe for the plucking.
I fear we must kill one another. It is Father's way. Two Children must not both leave a holy site alive.
Would you like to kill the old man, Jaheira, or shall I?
Fine, Sarevok. If she won't obey - take her as my offering instead.
You sacrificed your kin, the most sacred act a Bhaalian could conduct, and summoned him with her blood.
But for all your zeal, I sense something... amiss. You stand to be judged as an Unholy Assassin - and yet you bring no offering?
Very well. Then approach, and be judged.
You speak of the past - I speak of the future. Well, aspirant? Do the shades of yesterday speak for you, too?
What does Orin have to do with the murders in the city?
I defeated Orin. You are nothing.
But you will need my help.
But these are not aspirants. You have brought traitors of Bhaal into our midst.
Zeal.
Such stillness. Such nobility. Unmarked by your command.
*Sarevok Anchev. A relic of your cursed line, a Bhaalspawn who failed to become Chosen.*
And so it is that Orin now leads his Temple, and draws aspirants to his creed.
You gaze upon your disgraced kin, those who were sacrificed where you were raised up.
And when you do, remember grandfather Sarevok. Remember how he helped you. Return to visit him, and tell the blood-drenched tale of your victory.
Let us begin.
You misunderstand the Lord of Murder. He is not proud. He simply is.
Are you the one behind the murders in the city?
*In years past you brought this man low - foiled his plot to become a god. Now you stand before him, once again. Sarevok Anchev.*
Orin is your granddaughter?
Gesture for a kneel: an act, to see this sham of a ceremony through.
Worship death though I do, I refused it. I roamed the Coast, gathering those who still held Bhaal in their black hearts.
Ha. I killed Jaheira: your own slaughterer.
But Orin is not the subject of our judgement here today.
In combat. Honourably.
While you wriggled 'neath the city's soil like the worm that you are. It will please my hamster to kill you twice, Sarevok.
With these killings, the glory of the Bhaalists has risen beyond what we dreamed possible during those dark days.
Bhaal is about to name a new Chosen. All is between you and my granddaughter Orin now, and Orin has much to learn.
Why do you speak such heresy, child? Bhaal may favour you yet. You are the true inheritor after all.
My Lord made his choice - I abided by his words.
Does the fact that I killed Bhaal's own Chosen - Orin - not count for anything?
The Dread Lord will have his tribute - the blood spilled will be yours.
She may have usurped you once, but all her rites and rituals will never match her to your natural gift.
You are ripe for rebirth in his unholy name.
And when he does, remember grandfather Sarevok. Remember how he helped you. Return to visit him, and tell the blood-drenched tale of your victory.
It seems there is some disagreement on who is master here.
You follow me. You dare question the SLAYER-LORD?
Let us pave our own path. Starting with the kicked buttocks of that one there.
I know this one well. I have travelled in his company. Whatever else may be said of him, he answers to no one but Boo.
Walk well in the Dread Lord's bloody footsteps.
Unholy Chosen, of course you are above needing to prove yourself to the Tribunal.
You must be tested, Child. It is Bhaal's will.
You slaughter well, aspirant. You are deemed - worthy.
Your failure is known to the Lord of Murder. Your sentence is decreed.
As did I.
Simple. We beat him about the brow and butt until he was dead.

EditorData.NodeContext: No nonsense. Distastefully and bluntly telling the player how you know Sarevok.

Text.Value: Very well, lead on.
Your hubris has gained the better of you, as mine once did of me. But no more of this act.
But I do bring an offering, Sarevok. You've already met Minsc and Jaheira.
Minsc politely declines your offer to be an offering. I am afraid he is already claimed by Boo.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim - we've just offered him to Sarevok as a sacrifice. He's going to fight to the death.

Text.Value: What do you mean - vengeance?
Bhaal has never had a more gifted prodigy.
These are not aspirants. You have brought traitors of Bhaal into our midst.
*Before you is Sarevok Anchev - a Bhaalist who almost brought Baldur's Gate to ruin a century ago.*
I answer for myself, Sarevok - and Minsc answers to me. He won't be a problem.
It was her mother's blood that soaked the sheets. Orin had cut off the very hand that tried to end her, and made a plaything of it.
First, I ended its sorry existence. Then, I cut the hand from its corpse.
You're out of luck. I have escaped Bhaal's will.
You? You have slain Bhaal's Chosen?
Patience, child. Our Father has much in store for you.
Just to mingle your pissing fear with her gall-puddle. There are no words for this blasphemy.
I have no interest in being judged by Bhaal.
'Lay not a finger on this child,' he said, 'nor let any other, for this child will serve me with unholy ardour. Protect her, in my name.'
Our Father.
You shrink from that which you should revel in - it is in revelry that your devotion to the Lord of Murder is known.
I will save this city. A Bhaalspawn can have a true heart.
As you stood a statue, Stone Lord, a helpless ornament, your city changed. Warped. Became ripe for the plucking.
Forgive the... insolence. Master.

Text.Value: I would prefer to stoop over Sarevok's corpse.

EditorData.NodeContext: Quietly fuming, bowing because he was forced to

Text.Value: *The history they share may be long gone, but the threat of violence between them is as fresh as newly spilled blood - neither party will let the other walk out of here alive.*

I brought these two here as offerings for Bhaal.

I brought Minsc here as an offering for Bhaal.

She is the architect of Bhaal's design.
Order, and Minsc obeys. As if Boo himself commanded.

EditorData.NodeContext: Through gritted teeth - playing along with an act you hate

Text.Value: I'll happily challenge her. Where is she?
Before you may return to our Father's fold, I must first ensure that you remain as pure and worthy of his blessing as you once were.
It matters not, for you have entered empty-handed. Your sentence is decreed.
Your hubris is quite incredible - but it is your undoing, as it was once mine.
HIS FAITHFUL DEPARTED.
Before you may return to our Father's fold, I must first ensure that you remain as pure and worthy of his blessing as you once were.
I'll approach and take your head, monster.
Your hubris will be your undoing, as it was once mine.
You were murder. Pure murder. No excesses. No pretentions.
A victim does not know honour, a victim knows terror and pain.

Slowly and painfully. I savoured every scream.

But this is not her dwelling place. Orin resides within our Father's Temple.
Pathetic. Too afraid to die when you should have?
Sarevok, Bhaal's least favourite son. Still tied to daddy's apron strings, I see.
It is your right.
Fine, Sarevok. If they won't obey - take them as offerings instead.
Approach, aspirant, and be judged.
The violence pleases Bhaal. The domination pleases me. Your slaves may stand, the better to bear witness.
You have shown us the colour of your blood. Boo wonders if we had been wiser to spill it on the ground.

EditorData.NodeContext: Minsc bows before Sarevok, surprised and sad.

Text.Value: Does it hurt, Sarevok? To be confronted with yet another of your brood who is not so desperate for daddy's attention as you are?

You took their hands from them. Now, I will clutch one of their souls from the Abyss that they may show Bhaal who you are.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: the cloud of dark energy clears. The spectre of our previous victim stands before the player. It is confused, scared, and tries to speak, but no noise escapes.

Text.Value: Your fall was as spectacular as your birth - the purest Bhaalspawn there ever was, ruined by his own hubris.
Your fall was as spectacular as your birth - the purest Bhaalspawn there ever was, ruined by her own hubris.
Your fall was as spectacular as your birth - the purest Bhaalspawn there ever was, ruined by their own hubris.
I will be the Dread Lord's Chosen once again. And you will be my offering.
Orin only seeks the Bhaalian favour you were born to inherit.
I knew of my daughter's ambitions, but not the lengths to which she'd go.
I am the very Spawn of Bhaal. I need no leading.
Orin is your granddaughter?
Are you here to have your vengeance on my granddaughter, Orin?
Our Father does not feel pride. He bore the disgrace of creating life in his Spawn. We can but atone for the shame of birth.
Why are you pieces of jerky still alive?
*Sarevok Anchev. A Bhaalspawn who failed to become Chosen, long ago. A spilled stain of Father's Divine Essence left out to dry.*
But she only seeks the Bhaalian favour you were born to inherit.
I have already been sacrificed, centuries ago, upon Bhaal's own graven altar. I am now but a shadow of my former self.
We have both failed Bhaal, let us die again, this time by each other's hands in his holy site. Each breath you take is an insult to him.
I have no business with Bhaal, I'll leave.
You seem to know me. Have we met before?
This is where you reveal yourself.
With a smile on my face, and pleasure in my heart.
But you were foolish enough to think yourself untouchable. You didn't see Orin rising through the ranks.
Slowly and painfully. I savoured every scream.
Let us make a sacrifice of it, for Bhaal will have his offering.
But the worship of my Lord is led by another now - my granddaughter, Orin.
That's quite a story. Shame I had to kill Orin.
Wrong, Sarevok. I will lead his worship - you will be my offering to Bhaal.

EditorData.logicalname: SACRIFICED MINSC AND / OR JAHEIRA - SKIP RITUAL

Text.Value: To arms, then. In Bhaal's name.
Bhaal will never again have cause to question my devotion.
You toss allies aside so easily, after everything? If you are so eager to join this worm, then may you both be buried here together.

EditorData.NodeContext: First line is bitter realization. Then grim resignation - she's getting ready to fight us to the death.

With a smile on my face, and pleasure in my heart.
You want me to kill your own granddaughter?

Synopsis:
CINE ARTIST - PLEASE CONTACT WRITER RE. STRUCTURE - IT'S NOT THAT BAD, PROMISE
Dialog with Sarevok and his Murder Tribunal - will begin when approaching the Murder Tribunal in an underground area beneath Baldur's Gate. Sarevok will judge whether the player is worthy of receiving the title of "Unholy Assassin" - or tell the court to attack if we are deemed unworthy. If this part of the trial succeeds, the Tribunal will move on to the "Baptism of Blood" ritual (LOW_MurderTribunal_Sarevok_BloodBaptism).
